Title: Add arguments to side effects

Currently, event payloads are available in C but inaccessible from within
Smudge.  Thus, to access the data within an event you have to shell out to some
@function, which prevents or at least complicates a number of interesting use
cases, the largest of which is responding to events.

To address this, we can introduce the following concrete syntax.

For side-effects:

<<*>>=
-(e1 arg, @fn arg1 arg2, ...)-
@

For events handlers:

<<*>>=
[ event arg1 arg2 -(...)- ]
@

For events, this creates a struct with the corresponding number of fields of
the inferred types, allowing for defining the structure of events in Smudge,
instead of having to do it in C.  The scope of the name of the 'arg' variables
is the body of the side-effect list for that event.

For @fns, the semantics are as follows:
1) As in the current implementation, any @fn used in the context of only one
   event automatically gets a first argument of type event_t
2) As currently, any @fn used in multiple contexts get no such implicit argument
3) All explicit @fn arguments must match types exactly, and are put after the
   implicit argument if present, or otherwise are the only arguments.

Mismatching event handler parameters and args is a compiler error.

Giving an argument the same name as an event is a compiler error.
